elements.label: para
elements.text:
1) a) Suppose that $\lim _{t \to \infty}f(t)=\infty $. Can $f(t)$ ever decrease? If so, sketch a graph of an example. If
not, why not?

elements.label: para
elements.text: b) Suppose $\frac{4t-3}{t} \leq f(t) \leq \frac{4t^{5}+7}{t^{5}-3}$ when $t>92$. Determine $\lim _{t \to \infty} f(t)$.

elements.label: para
elements.text:
c) Design a rational function for which $\lim _{t\to 4}f(t)$ is a ${\frac {0}{0}}$ indeterminate form, but the actual value of
the limit is ${\sqrt {2}}$

elements.label: para
elements.text: d) Sketch graphs of function $f$ and $g(\neq 0)$ so that $\lim _{t \to 0} f(t) g(t)$ exists, but $\lim _{t \to 0} f(t)$ does not.

elements.label: para
elements.text:
e) Suppose $|f(x)-7|<10^{-3}$ whenever $0<|x-5|<0.0001$. What do we know about
$\lim _{x\to 5}f(x)$?

elements.label: para

elements.text: 4) Provide a rigorous proof (i.e. a $\delta-\varepsilon$ proof) that $\lim _{x \to 3}\left(x^{2}-x-6\right)=0$.

elements.label: para
elements.text:
5) Find the dimensions of the rectangle of largest area that has its base on the y-axis and its other
two vertices on the right side of the y-axis and lying on the parabola $x=9-y^{2}$.

elements.label: para
elements.text:
6) Sketch the graph of the function $f(x)=1+{\frac {1}{x}}+{\frac {1}{x^{2}}}$ noting any maximum and minimum points,
points of inflection, vertical tangents, and asymptotes, as well as intervals of increase and decrease,
convexity and concavity.

elements.label: para
elements.text:
7) Let $\mathfrak{R}$ be the region in the first quadrant bounded by the curves $y=x^{3}$ and $y=3x-2x^{2}$.
Provide a sketch of the region, and calculate the following quantities:

elements.label: list
elements.text:
(i) The area of $\mathfrak{R}$
(ii) The volume obtained by rotating $\mathfrak{R}$ about the $x$-axis; use the washer method.
(iii)The volume obtained by rotating $\mathfrak{R}$ about the $y$-axis; use the shell method.

elements.text: b) Evaluate the integrating factor, and use it to solve the differential equation: $x y'+y=\sqrt{x}$
